You can configure the footer area of the theme from the settings option. You will find all relevant section settings to the "Footer" option. Navigate to <strong>Theme Options &gt; Footer Settings </strong>to go to this settings section. We provided all necessary instructions and descriptions with all the options.

<a href="http://wordpress.creativegigs.net/docly/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/footer.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-2192 size-full" src="http://wordpress.creativegigs.net/docly/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/footer.png" alt="" width="1313" height="623" /></a>

&nbsp;

Go to <em><strong><span style="color: #000000;">Appearance &gt; Customize &gt; Site Identity</span>.</strong></em> Then Select an image as site icon. It's recommended to use a <strong><em>.ico</em></strong> image as the site icon (favicon).

<a href="http://wordpress.creativegigs.net/docly/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/favicon.png"><img class="alignnone wp-image-2218 size-full" src="http://wordpress.creativegigs.net/docly/wp-content/uploads/2017/01/favicon.png" alt="" width="461" height="501" /></a>

&nbsp;

wp:comment.wp:comment_content:
If you need special things—[shortcodes], paragraph tags, anything exciting—in the content, you should apply the filters as opposed to using do_shortcode().


$post   = get_post( 42 );
$output =  apply_filters( 'the_content', $post-&gt;post_content );


Thanks

Note that get_the_content doesn’t return the same thing as what the_content displays. For that you need to do this:
<pre>
$content = apply_filters( 'the_content', get_the_content() );
echo $content;
</pre>

If you are wanting to check if a custom (non core block) is for a page or post, include the namespace/name-of-block:

<pre>
if ( has_block( 'my-namespace/block-name' ) ) {
 // Do stuff here.
}
</pre>

